PLANS are under way to declare the drought a national disaster by next week. Yesterday the Inter-Ministerial Task Team on Drought and Water Scarcity’s chairman, Co-operative Governance Minister Des van Rooyen, was speaking in Cape Town.He said: “The process will be finalised before Wednesday. if(typeof za24_DisplayAd != "undefined") za24_DisplayAd("300x250","2");<a href="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/jump?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" target="_blank"><img src="https://pubads.g.doubleclick.net/gampad/ad?iu=0&sz=1&c=234" border="0" alt=""></a>“This will legally hand over responsibility for co-ordinating the disaster to the national executive.” This declaration will empower the minister or a delegate to issue regulations to deal with the disaster. “We are convinced this will improve current measures to deal with it. “It will also ensure that provinces which are not currently declared can be covered through measures to prevent and ease the drought situation,” said Van Rooyen.“In August R74,8 million was given to Western Cape to deal with the situation. “The only challenge is the slow pace of using the allocated funding to lessen the impact of the drought on certain sectors.” According to the task team, which also involves Water Minister Nomvula Mokonyane and Agriculture Minister Senzeni Zokwana, the drought is also affecting Northern Cape and Eastern Cape.“We are considering requests from those provinces for funding of response and recovery measures,” said Van Rooyen. The national dam level average currently stands at 59,6%. Gauteng has the highest levels at 94,6%, while Western Cape is the lowest at 23,7%. “The government appeals to all South Africans and visitors to help save water,” said Van Rooyen.